            "summary": "A low liver disease score means that your blood is showing signs of damage to the liver either from alcohol or a viral hepatitis.",
            "description": "Liver disease (also called hepatic disease) is a type of damage to or disease of the liver. Liver disease can occur through several mechanisms. A common form of liver disease is viral infection. Viral hepatitides such as Hepatitis B virus and Hepatitis C virus can be vertically transmitted during birth via contact with infected blood. High consumption of alcohol can lead to several forms of liver disease including alcoholic hepatitis, alcoholic fatty liver disease, cirrhosis, and liver cancer. In the earlier stages of alcoholic liver disease, fat builds up in the liver's cells due to increased creation of triglycerides and fatty acids and a decreased ability to break down fatty acids. Progression of the disease can lead to liver inflammation from the excess fat in the liver. Scarring in the liver often occurs as the body attempts to heal and extensive scarring can lead to the development of cirrhosis in more advanced stages of the disease. Approximately 3-10% of individuals with cirrhosis develop a form of liver cancer known as hepatocellular carcinoma.",

            "score": 8,
            "name": "Liver health",
            "summary": "Everything you consume passes through the liver before reaching organs and tissues; it is the workhorse of your body, ensuring nutrients, medications, hormones, and toxic substances are handled appropriately.",
            "description": "The liver is a critical organ that performs over 500 functions vital for life. It is the primary detoxification organ, and also plays a role in aiding digestion, making energy, and balancing hormones. It processes everything you consume, including all medications, supplements, and chemical exposures. Most proteins, including those involved in wound healing and immune processes, are made in the liver as well. Your liver is resilient and will continue to function, even if two-thirds of it has been damaged. Despite this, blood markers can help you identify how your liver is functioning.↵↵Eating a healthy diet, reducing or avoiding alcohol consumption, and exercising caution with over-the-counter drugs and supplements all help with maintaining proper liver function.",

            "name": "Kidney health",
            "summary": "Your kidneys have many jobs but most importantly they filter waste, make urine, and regulate blood pressure.",
            "description": "The kidneys are two fist-sized organs underneath your rib cage. They regulate blood pressure and filter wastes and toxins from the blood. It is different from irritable bowels, painful gas, or food intolerances. A low IBD score means your blood is showing patterns similar to individuals with IBD.",
            "description": "Inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) involves chronic inflammation of all or part of your digestive tract. Inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) is a term mainly used to describe two conditions, ulcerative colitis and Crohn's disease. Both ulcerative colitis and Crohn's disease are long-term (chronic) conditions that involve inflammation of the gut (gastrointestinal tract). Ulcerative colitis only affects the colon (large intestine), while Crohn's disease can affect all of the digestive system, from the mouth to the anus. Both usually involve severe diarrhea, pain, fatigue and weight loss. IBD can be debilitating and sometimes leads to life-threatening complications. The exact cause of inflammatory bowel disease remains unknown. Previously, diet and stress were suspected, but now doctors know that these factors may aggravate but don't cause IBD. One possible cause is an immune system malfunction. When your immune system tries to fight off an invading virus or bacterium, an abnormal immune response causes the immune system to attack the cells in the digestive tract, too. Heredity also seems to play a role in that IBD is more common in people who have family members with the disease. However, most people with IBD don't have this family history.",

            "description": "Rheumatoid arthritis (RA) is an autoimmune disease. If the inflammation goes unchecked, it can damage cartilage, the elastic tissue that covers the ends of bones in a joint, as well as the bones themselves.\r\n\r\nOur assessment looks at nutrients, inflammatory markers, and immune system proteins as they contribute to RA. It also includes markers known to be altered in individuals with RA. A plant-rich diet, along with omega-3 fats, and fat soluble vitamins can improve RA symptoms.             "description": "Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) is an umbrella term used to describe progressive lung diseases including emphysema, chronic bronchitis, and non-reversible asthma.             "description": "Nonalcoholic fatty liver disease is a term used to describe the accumulation of fat in the liver of people who drink little or no alcohol. This more serious form of nonalcoholic fatty liver disease is sometimes called nonalcoholic steatohepatitis. At its most severe, nonalcoholic fatty liver disease can progress to liver failure. Nonalcoholic fatty liver disease usually causes no signs and symptoms. When it does, they may include fatigue, pain in the upper right abdomen, and weight loss. \r\n\r\nNonalcoholic fatty liver disease occurs when your liver has trouble breaking down fats, causing fat to build up in your liver tissue. Doctors aren't sure what causes nonalcoholic fatty liver disease. The wide range of diseases and conditions linked to nonalcoholic fatty liver disease is so diverse that it's difficult to pinpoint any one cause.\r\n\r\nNonalcoholic fatty liver disease can take several forms — from harmless to life-threatening.
